A center in another basis

This resonates with mathematics.

A system may have no obvious center in Cartesian coordinates but have one in another basis.

For example:

* A cloud has no geometric center that explains it well, but it may have a statistical center.
* A conversation may have no central speaker, but it has a central theme.
* A company may not revolve around one person, but around a mission or incentive structure.
* An ecosystem may not have a “leader,” but energy flow creates organizing gradients.
* A network may lack a geometric center but have nodes with high connectivity or influence.

Changing basis reveals different invariants.

So instead of asking:

“Where is the center?”

You can ask:

“In what coordinate system does this system become simplest?”

Sometimes the “center” is not spatial at all.

It might be:

* informational,
* causal,
* energetic,
* semantic,
* temporal,
* motivational,
* economic.

Finding the right basis is often more valuable than finding the center.

